Absolutely! Here’s a simple example: a chatbot app code using *JavaScript* that can run in a basic web app (you can later connect it to AI APIs like OpenAI’s GPT for smarter replies).

This chatbot will respond to user messages with simple comforting replies to help alone people feel heard.

```javascript
// Simple chatbot logic
const responses = [
  "I'm here for you. Tell me more.",
  "That sounds tough, but you're not alone.",
  "I'm listening. What's on your mind?",
  "It's okay to feel that way.",
  "You're doing great. Keep going!"
];

function getResponse() {
  // Return a random comforting message
  const index = Math.floor(Math.random() * responses.length);
  return responses[index];
}

function sendMessage() {
  const userInput = document.getElementById("userInput").value;
  if (userInput.trim() === "") return;

  // Display user's message
  const chatBox = document.getElementById("chatBox");
  chatBox.innerHTML += `<div class="user-msg">You: userInput</div>`;

  // Get bot response
  const botReply = getResponse();
  chatBox.innerHTML += `<div class="bot-msg">Bot:{botReply}</div>`;

  document.getElementById("userInput").value = "";
  chatBox.scrollTop = chatBox.scrollHeight;
}
```

